<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">One question runs through the whole unit: can you meet your daily needs here on foot?</p>
  <p>The <strong>15-minute neighborhood</strong> is a place where the things you do every day (live, work, shop, learn, heal, play, and move) sit within a short walk or cycle of home. When a place is built that way, the car becomes optional rather than mandatory. When it is not, every errand becomes a trip, and the people without a car or scooter pay the highest price in time, money, and exposure to heat and traffic. So the question "can you live here on foot?" is not a lifestyle preference. It is a question about how land near homes gets used, and who that use serves.</p>
  <p>Chennai is a sharp test case. The city has grown fast, paved over wetlands and <em>eris</em> (the old rain-fed tanks that once held the monsoon), flooded badly in 2015, and now bakes through longer, hotter dry seasons. Dense informal settlements sit next to gated towers, and access to green space, clinics, and safe footpaths is wildly uneven. Redesigning a neighborhood to work on foot means deciding how to use limited land, and there is no design that wins on every front at once. That tension is the engine of this unit.</p>
  <p>This is the same move you have been building all year, widened one more step. In <a href="/units/unit-5/">Unit 5</a> you weighed competing claims over water. A water claim, it turns out, is also a land claim: the paddy that needs the water sits on land, and so does the housing, the wetland, and the road. Unit 6 takes the trade-off reasoning from water to the built environment people actually live in. By Block 9 you will present your own neighborhood redesign in public. Today the question just lands.</p>
</section>

