<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end with a short walkability read of a real place plus the first trade-off you notice. The path is about how you build that read.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I can explain the 15-minute-neighborhood idea and name at least three competing things a neighborhood has to deliver at once.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Walkability audit of your area (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Pick the area around your home. For each of the daily needs (live, work or school, shop for food, learn, healthcare, play or green space, and move), mark reachable on foot in 15 minutes or not. Write one sentence on the need that is hardest to reach and why.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Compare two areas (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Audit two different Chennai areas you know (for example a dense older neighborhood and a newer gated layout). What does each do well for walkability, and what does each give up to get it? This is your first look at a trade-off: the thing one area gained by sacrificing another.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Map a non-driver's day (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Trace a normal day for someone in your area who does not drive: a young child, an older relative, a domestic worker, a street vendor. Where can they get on foot, and where are they stuck? Walkability is not the same for everyone, and that gap is the start of the equity thread this unit returns to.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Peer-help — what counts as a daily need (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If it is unclear what to count, come to the peer-help table. Build the list of daily needs together with a partner and Mr. Ignash, then audit one shared area as a pair. The point is to leave with a working definition you can reuse.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section show">
  <span class="section-tag">Show</span>
  <h2>What you're submitting today</h2>
  <p class="sub">A short walkability read plus the first trade-off you noticed. Specific beats general.</p>
  <div class="submission-callout">
    <div class="label">Exit ticket — walkability read + first trade-off</div>
    <p>Three things: (1) name 5 daily needs and whether each is reachable on foot in 15 minutes where you looked, (2) name the need that is hardest to reach and why, and (3) one sentence naming a trade-off you already see (to get more of one thing, the area gave up another). Generic ("it needs more facilities") does not clear the bar. Specific does, for example: "this layout fits a lot of housing but left almost no shaded park, so children play on the road."</p>
    <a href="#" class="rubric-link">Submit via Google Classroom →</a>
  </div>
  <p class="rubric-meta">
    <strong>Rubric link:</strong> naming a real trade-off, even roughly, is the first step toward the Thinking and Transfer gate on the <a href="/units/unit-6/assessment-sustainable-neighborhood-plan/">Sustainable Neighborhood Plan</a>. That gate rewards plans that name what they sacrificed. See the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>.
  </p>
</section>

